name: Frame_Unboundedness
hasDescription:
["or other thing is spatially and/or temporally bounded or finite. This is the opposite of Unboundedness. Note that terms such as 'boundless' evoke a concept of (lack of) limits", 'unbounded things are limitless: we can continue to use them without using them up. 

When our confidence is boundless', 'An entity', 'we are likely to eventually run out of it.  For instance', 'without worrying that we won’t have enough confidence to complete the task.', 'limited quantity. If it’s something that decreases in quantity when we use it', 'once we drink it', 'we won’t have any more water in our cup.  On the other hand', 'we feel we can take on any challenge', 'if we have a cup of water', "terms such as 'infinite' do not necessarily do so.

Bounded things have a finite", 'process']
label: ['Unboundedness']

Motion-affecting objects (e.g. burdens and restraints)

It can be recreated again in the future if necessary.

It has other special cases, specialized by type of impediment.

Its opposite is Enablement."]

hasDescription: ['Evaluation typically involves both identification (e.g. what something is', 'such as feelings of pain or pleasure', 'or more complex emotional states.', "and what properties it has) and present relevance (how does this thing contribute to the evaluator's current needs and goals?). Evaluation is typically a part of decision making: one evaluates options prior to deciding what to do.\n\nIn some cases (e.g. positive/negative evaluations that involve emotions)", "the 'present relevance' will largely be the evaluator's internal state"]
label: ['Evaluation']

hasDescription: ['especially the urge to acquire (and act on) something. name: Frame_Seeing
hasDescription: ['This frame is specific to visual perception of some entity or situation']
label: ['Seeing']
comment:
["The LU 'see' may be problematic for extraction

Unlike FrameNet's 'Perception_experience' frame, this frame is specific to vision.
Parameters that affect the See-er's ability to see an object include:
- light conditions around seen_object
- degree of obstruction
- visual acuity of See-er
- distance between See-er and Seen_object
- perspective from which See-er sees seen_object
- visually-accessible parts of the Object_seen
- See-er’s visual area (focal area, and overall field of vision) 
- distance between See-er and seen_object"]

comment:
['Democratic institutions are numerous formal and informal conventional practices, laws, rules, and norms that are crucial for democratic laws and principles (along with the equality and freedom associated with democracy) to be practiced. Representation and decision-making are amongst the valued institutions of a recognized democracy, in addition to free economic institutions 
(including capitalism), political institutions, and social institutions.

The relevant democratic institutions which are relevant to a comparative cross-linguistic and cross-cultural study of metaphors include: free speech/freedom of expression, freedom of the press, unions, elections, educational institutions, health and welfare institutions, property rights, assembly and political parties, judicial and legal institutions.']

hasDescription:
['Confidence is the belief in the reliability or truth of yourself or another person or thing.

People who are confident are certain in their beliefs about the world and about their ability to do well in life.  Confident people trust in themselves to make good decisions and to act in an appropriate way. 

Self-confident people trust in their own abilities and opinions.  When they are presented with an opportunity', 'without doubting themselves or fearing that they are doing the wrong thing.', 'they act with certainty and purpose']
